eq 0$ has a neighborhood $W$ which is mapped into the open set $B$ by some $S \in \Gamma$. Since $T$ is a compact operator, $K=\overline{T(B)}$ is a compact set. By (5), $0 
otin K$. Therefore there are open sets $W_{1}, \ldots, W_{n}$, whose union covers $K$, such that $S_{i}\left(W_{i}ight) \subset B$ for some $S_{i} \in \Gamma, 1 \leq i \leq n$. Put  $$ \mu=\max \left\{\left\|S_{1}ight\|, \ldots,\left\|S_{n}ight\|ight\} $$  Starting with $x_{0}, T x_{0}$ lies in $K$, hence in some $W_{i_{1}}$, and $S_{i_{1}} T x_{0} \in$ $B$. Therefore $T S_{i_{1}} T x_{0}$ lies in $K$, hence in some $W_{i_{2}}$, and $S_{i_{2}} T S_{i_{1}} T X_{0}$ is back in $B$. Continuing this ping-pong game, we obtain vectors  $$ x_{N}=S_{i_{N}} T \cdots S_{i_{1}} T x_{0}=S_{i_{N}} \cdots S_{i_{1}} T^{N} x_{0} $$  in $B$. Hence  $$  rac{1}{2}\left\|x_{0}ight\| \leq\left\|x_{N}ight\| \leq \mu^{N}\left\|T^{N}ight\|\left\|x_{0}ight\| \quad(N=1,2,3, \ldots) $$  and this gives information about the spectral radius of $T$, namely,  $$ ho(T)=\lim _{N ightarrow \infty}\left\|T^{N}ight\|^{1 / N} \geq  rac{1}{\mu}>0 $$  We now invoke Theorem 4.25. Since $ho(T)>0, T$ has an eigenvalue $\lambda 
eq 0$. The corresponding eigenspace  $$ M_{\lambda}=\{x \in X: T x=\lambda x\} $$  is finite-dimensional; hence $M_{\lambda} 
eq X$. If $S \in \Gamma$ and $x \in M_{\lambda}$, then  $$ T(S x)=S(T x)=S(\lambda x)=\lambda S x $$  so that $S x \in M_{\lambda}$. This says that $S\left(M_{\lambda}ight) \subset M_{\lambda}$.  Thus $M_{\lambda}$ satisfies the conclusion of the theorem, even though we assumed that this conclusion failed.

